EV Charging Standards
---------------------

From CNBC ( https://www.cnbc.com/2023/06/08/gm-tesla-partner-on-ev-charging=
-network.html ) :

General Motors will follow crosstown rival Ford Motor in partnering with Te=
sla to use the electric vehicle leader=E2=80=99s North American charging ne=
twork and technologies. Under the deal, GM vehicles will be able to access =
12,000 of Tesla=E2=80=99s fast chargers using an adapter and the Detroit au=
tomaker=E2=80=99s EV charging app, starting next year. GM, like Ford, will =
also begin installing a charging port used by Tesla known as NACS, or the N=
orth American Charging Standard, instead of the current industry-standard C=
CS, in its EVs starting in 2025.

GM CEO Mary Barra told CNBC=E2=80=99s Phil LeBeau on Thursday that, as a re=
sult of a deal, the automaker expects to save up to $400 million of a previ=
ously announced $750 million investment to build out EV charging. The partn=
erships with now two leading Detroit automakers is a major win for Tesla an=
d its charging technology. It is expected to add pressure on other automake=
rs =E2=80=94 as well as the U.S. government, which is investing billions in=
 building out an EV charging network =E2=80=94 to adopt Tesla=E2=80=99s tec=
hnology.

Wall Street analysts hailed the Tesla-Ford deal as a =E2=80=9Cwin-win=E2=80=
=9D when that deal was announced last month. Both GM and Tesla stocks were =
up about 3% during after-hours trading Thursday. The deal was announced by =
Barra and Tesla CEO Elon Musk during a live audio discussion on Twitter Spa=
ces. It comes as GM ramps up production of its fully electric vehicles in p=
ursuit of Tesla-level sales volumes in the segment.

I don=E2=80=99t generally cover the electric vehicle market, but I think th=
at this announcement =E2=80=94 which was quickly followed by an announcemen=
t from Rivian ( https://twitter.com/Rivian/status/1671141789439492097 ) , i=
n addition to the prior announcement from Ford =E2=80=94 is pretty interest=
ing on multiple dimensions.

First, it=E2=80=99s worth pointing out that Tesla=E2=80=99s NACS standard i=
s just flat-out better than CCS; this Article from Electrek ( https://elect=
rek.co/2023/06/05/tesla-ford-partnership-charging-standard-angers-ccs-coali=
tion/ ) provides a good overview, but I think this is a situation where a p=
icture is worth a thousand words:

A comparison of various EV charging standards ( https://electrek.co/2023/06=
/05/tesla-ford-partnership-charging-standard-angers-ccs-coalition/ )

This illustration is from Tesla ( https://www.tesla.com/blog/opening-north-=
american-charging-standard ) :

Comparing Tesla's charger to the alternative ( https://www.tesla.com/blog/o=
pening-north-american-charging-standard )

From what I can gather =E2=80=94 again, see the caveat about electric cars =
not being my speciality =E2=80=94 the CCS standard is a classic design-by-c=
ommittee failure: it starts with a requirement of being backwards compatibl=
e to a charger that, by definition, was not widely used (because there simp=
ly weren=E2=80=99t that many electric cars), and also has a whole host of c=
apabilities built in for future use cases. This latter point sounds good in=
 theory, but the fact that it increasingly feels inevitable that Tesla=E2=
=80=99s design will win in North America shows the fallacy involved in spen=
ding too much time and effort and, critically, diminishment in the user exp=
erience, in building for future use cases: it=E2=80=99s all pointless if yo=
u don=E2=80=99t win the present, because you won=E2=80=99t even be present =
in the future.

The other thing that Tesla had going for them was reliability. Tesla superc=
hargers simply work, nearly every time, while 3rd-party charging providers =
have notorious reliability issues, which is a major issue when it comes to =
committing to an electric car: the fact that you knew a Tesla charger would=
 work was a major reason to take the plunge.

That, though, gets at why this announcement is so interesting: Tesla=E2=80=
=99s Supercharger network was a reason to get a Tesla.

Tesla=E2=80=99s Strategy
----------------

One of the long-running themes on Stratechery is about the difference betwe=
en horizontal and vertical companies. Apple is the classic example of the l=
atter: the company makes money from selling hardware, so its software diffe=
rentiation is in service to differentiating its hardware. Google, on the ot=
her hand, is a horizontal company: it is in the company=E2=80=99s interest =
to provide a great experience to iOS customers as well as to Android custom=
ers.

Until late last year the Supercharger network suggested that Tesla was purs=
uing a vertical strategy: it was, as I noted above, a reason to buy a Tesla=
. That changed, though, with this blog post from last November ( https://ww=
w.tesla.com/blog/opening-north-american-charging-standard ) :

With more than a decade of use and 20 billion EV charging miles to its name=
, the Tesla charging connector is the most proven in North America, offerin=
g AC charging and up to 1 MW DC charging in one slim package. It has no mov=
ing parts, is half the size, and twice as powerful as Combined Charging Sys=
tem (CCS) connectors.

In pursuit of our mission to accelerate the world=E2=80=99s transition to s=
ustainable energy, today we are opening our EV connector design to the worl=
d. We invite charging network operators and vehicle manufacturers to put th=
e Tesla charging connector and charge port, now called the North American C=
harging Standard (NACS), on their equipment and vehicles. NACS is the most =
common charging standard in North America: NACS vehicles outnumber CCS two-=
to-one, and Tesla=E2=80=99s Supercharging network has 60% more NACS posts t=
han all the CCS-equipped networks combined.

Network operators already have plans in motion to incorporate NACS at their=
 chargers, so Tesla owners can look forward to charging at other networks w=
ithout adapters. Similarly, we look forward to future electric vehicles inc=
orporating the NACS design and charging at Tesla=E2=80=99s North American S=
upercharging ( https://www.tesla.com/supercharger ) and Destination Chargin=
g ( https://www.tesla.com/destination-charging ) networks.

As a purely electrical and mechanical interface agnostic to use case and co=
mmunication protocol, NACS is straightforward to adopt. The design and spec=
ification files are available for download ( https://www.tesla.com/support/=
charging-product-guides#NACS-resources ) , and we are actively working with=
 relevant standards bodies to codify Tesla=E2=80=99s charging connector as =
a public standard. Enjoy.

The first paragraph covers the superior physical design I noted above. The =
second paragraph is the inverse of the vertical strategy bit I laid out: NA=
CS is the most widely used charger because Tesla sells the most electric ve=
hicles. The first part of the third paragraph, meanwhile, is in-line with T=
esla=E2=80=99s seemingly vertical strategy; Apple, to take a relevant examp=
le, is happy to have other companies sell iPhone cases and charging cables,=
 and surely it is good for Tesla to have even more chargers available to Te=
sla owners.

It=E2=80=99s the second sentence in that paragraph, though, that is the shi=
ft in strategy: =E2=80=9Cfuture electric vehicles incorporating the NACS de=
sign and charging at Tesla=E2=80=99s North American Supercharging and Desti=
nation Charging networks=E2=80=9D. This is very much a horizontal strategy:=
 Tesla is giving other electric car makers access to something that differe=
ntiates their own vehicles.

This leads to the most interesting question of all: why?

Tesla=E2=80=99s Reward
--------------

Tesla=E2=80=99s argument is that they simply want to see electric vehicles =
succeed, and granting more vehicles access to Tesla=E2=80=99s network certa=
inly helps accomplish that, so it may be true! It may also, to be fair, be =
a bit of a Strategy Credit ( https://stratechery.com/2013/strategy-credit/?=
access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9u=
