The second reason is that while Tesla may be dominant in the market today, =
its share will inevitably decrease as all vehicles become electric; that wo=
uld, in the long run, inevitably mean that the CCS networks would be better=
, which means that Tesla had a closing window within which to establish NAC=
S as the standard (which both supports the CCS protocol and also Tesla=E2=
=80=99s own proprietary protocol, which means that Tesla can still deliver =
a superior experience to its own cars).

A second implication of this view is that while access to the Tesla network=
 is right now a positive differentiator, only having access to Tesla=E2=80=
=99s network might at some point be a negative differentiator. However, if =
Tesla successfully makes NACS the North American standard, then at least it=
 can have a nice =E2=80=9Cgas station=E2=80=9D business controlling a big c=
hunk of superchargers that, by virtue of being first, are in prime location=
s.

I actually think that both of these first two reasons are sufficient to jus=
tify this change. I suspect, though, that Tesla is actually getting a nice =
high margin business out of this as well. At first glance, that blog post a=
bove, with its talk about openness and public standards, makes it sound lik=
e NCAS is free, which also seems to align to with Tesla=E2=80=99s long-stan=
ding patent pledge.

On the other hand, it does seem notable that Ford, GM, and Rivian all had t=
o announce agreements with Tesla, not just adoption, and that various repor=
ts say that the adapters they will send to current owners are locked to the=
ir vehicle. That definitely suggests a licensing regime. Which, I would not=
e, fits with Tesla=E2=80=99s patent pledge ( https://www.lexology.com/libra=
ry/detail.aspx?g=3Dca6c332f-2cc5-401b-b80d-36473d0754c7 ) , which explicitl=
y rules out directly competing designs or products, of which the NCAS adapt=
er surely is one.

In short, while the timing of Tesla=E2=80=99s shift may have been driven by=
 the explosion in alternative electric vehicles (and, I should note, federa=
l subsidies for chargers that mandate supporting multiple brands), the comp=
any definitely stands to make money off of this shift to being a horizontal=
 charging standard provider. And, I would add, I think that=E2=80=99s perfe=
ctly fine: there are a lot of people up-in-arms about Tesla controlling thi=
s standard, but to my mind that is exactly the sort of award befitting Tesl=
a=E2=80=99s massive contribution in making electric cool in the first place=
